description.text:
This is a replacement hinge for the slow close Bevis brand toilet seat. The original from them breaks easy due to the stress of the slow close spring mechanism.

My test hinge is currently being... tested. I printed it at a 25% infill, but once I'm convinced it is correct, I will reprint with a 100% or so infill. I printed mine with full supports, however, I don't believe they are needed, I just didn't want to print it 12 times.

This is my 2nd attempt. The first one wasn't high enough and when the unsuspecting person sat on it, it broke. Yeah, feel free to shorten it for some quick humor.

I had included the 123D file so you can feel free to try to alter it if needed.

The best way to print this is on its side. The failure point moves from the layer lines along the hinge to an interrior part. This keeps the hinge intact, but the slow close fails. Well, so far.

description.text:
Do you have single-issue comic books that you want to put on your bookshelf, along with your hardcovers and trade paperbacks? The Comic Backstrip is the simple solution to get your favorite comics out of your longboxes and on your bookshelves, where they belong.

This model uses OpenSCAD to allow customization of the size of the backstrip. You will need to tell the customizer the thickness, in mm, of your story collection. There is no simple equation to say what thickness a certain number of comics are. Some issues have more pages than others, have thicker stock of covers. For example, my 9 issue collection of Blackest Night is 22mm, while my 9 issue collection of Warren Ellis' Fell is only 16mm. The latter is the norm, as Blackest Night is made up of larger books. I used calipers to measure the thickness of the collections.

Included with the script and part pieces is a sample 20mm backstrip. This size fits collections that range from 7 to 14 issues.

This design includes a slot for labels. I design the labels in Photoshop, and print them at Walmart or CVS using their same-day 4x6 glossy photo prints.

Printer:

Makerfarm Pegasus 10"

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

400 micron

Infill:

Doesn't matter

Notes:

The Thingiverse Customizer is not compatible with the import commands that my OpenSCAD script uses. Instead, I've uploaded a ZIP file with a batch. It will ask for the width, and will then generate the STL file of a backstrip at that width. The batch is tested to work on Windows machines that have OpenSCAD x64 installed in its original location on the C drive. Otherwise, you can manually open the OpenSCAD script and change the size variable.

I print these at .4mm layer height using my .8mm nozzle, though I imagine a .2mm resolution would work just fine. At 400 micron, though, you might need to be a little careful that the label slot comes through. I had to make sure to print at a 90% extrusion rate for PLA.

On smaller backstrips, supports will not be needed for most printers, but as they get larger, the demand for bridging becomes more. I used supports for the Saga backstrip, with the first few mm worth removed thanks to S3D's support system.

You may also need to use rafts for larger backstripts. The Saga backstrip I made is 65mm wide, which is what I believe led to my first print attempt of it to fail about 80% in, when it fell over.

I've been a comic book nerd for 13 years. (My first comic book was Identity Crisis #1.) There are many different kinds of comic book fans. One difference are the readers and the collectors. Collectors are on the lookout for special covers, number ones. They have large collections of comic book issues is 'longboxes'. I am not a collector; I am a reader. I only buy my comics to read them. Problem is, it is a bit awkward to then have all of your comics stored in boxes in your closet. I've always wanted a way to display the collections of single-issue comics that I would want to go back to read, along side my trade paperbacks and hardcovers.

I originally did this by making custom-sized magazine file boxes out of cardboard and colored duct tape. It didn't work out very well, though, as they fell apart too easily. But for the longest time, that was my only real option.

Now that I have a 3D printer, I have what I need to solve this problem. At first I was trying to create entire boxes, the same size of the magazine file boxes I had made before. This took too much material; I calculated I could only make up to 10 of these boxes for each 1KG of filament spool.

Then I realized that I don't need an entire box. These comics are going to be on a bookshelf, in between my trade paperbacks and other single-issue collections. All I need is something to help me identify what each collection is. Like a book spine, a backstrip.

The backstrip is the design of a book's spine. It's the book title, the author.

I designed this in Tinkercad. The model is in three parts, the left and right, and the center. I then used OpenSCAD (for the first time), to allow an easy way to customize the center, allowing for custom sized models of the backstrip.

Anemometer used for the automatization of the garden sliding shade. Basically, print 3 cups, then print the cover, insert the cups into the openings within the cover and apply the thin CA glue to fix it. Print the tower and insert the bearing 608ZZ into the tip of the tower. Once it's done, the cover with the cups can be inserted into the bearing as well, allowing the smooth operation.
Once it's assembled, drill the 5mm hole through the cover and the tower, insert the 5x4mm cylinder magnet into the cover and fix it using the thin CA glue, use the drilled hole in tower to mount there the hall sensor that will sense the magnet each time it passes. Secure the hall sensor with the silicone to make it water resistant.
Use the hole at the bottom of the tower for the wire, allowing the connection to the rest of the automation system.

description.text:
This electric box is for connecting the servo, 2 Hotend Fan's and a printer fan on a Ramps 1.4 board. The Fan's are using PWM from Servoports D4, D5 and D6. The servo is connected to port D11. The guide is original from the D.E.I.S.S Extruder https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:651723

The PCB is drawn in Target 3001. I have milled it on my CNC milling cutter.

The box is mounted above the servo

Extract from D.E.I.S.S Setup Guide:

Setup electronics
The servo needs to be powerful enough to move the engine and provide the torque to move it against the spring of the levers. The RAMPs (the Arduino Mega) is a very powerful, powerful, and easy-to-use tool that can be used in a wide range of applications. This could be done by adding a 5V regulator which is directly driven by the 12V power supply. I created a small hand soldered PCB which also expands the D4 to D6 to drive a fan. The schematics are shown below. From this PCB, the servo is supplied with 5V as well as the servo signal, the fan fan, the cooling fan and a spare channel for the stepper driver and polyswitch (prevents the bed cut off at higher temperatures) , There are several pre-soldered 5V step-down regulators and fan expanders available on the internet which could be used without soldering.
D4 = Print fan
D5 = Hotend0 fan (activated at temperature above 50 ° C)
D6 = Hotend1 fan (activated at temperature above 50 ° C)
D11 = Servo output

Store well over a dozen eggs on this compact and elegant bench top ramp. The eggs automatically flip from the upper ramp to the lower one so they stay in order. This is important for those of us who have chooks and get our eggs a few each day. Even if your buy your eggs by the dozen, this is still a fun way to display them. http://youtu.be/5ALTPbibgh0

All parts were printed with 0.3mm layer height and 40% fill but this isn't critical. The flip cup incorporates support into the design - you don't need to add your own.  
Timber parts are 400mm and 350mm long, 28mm concave corner mouldings.  The shorter one is cut at an angle to match the angle of the cup when it swings up.  After test fitting everything together I dismantled it again and gave the timber 2 coats of polyurethane.  You can make the ramps longer or shorter if you wish to store more eggs or occupy less bench space respectively.  
A dozen small wood screws hold plastic parts to timber and I used a fine nail for the flip cup pivot.  I snipped the nail to length and flattened the cut end in a vise to stop it falling out.  You could open up the holes with a drill and use 2 small screws or some 3mm filament for the pivot instead if you wish.   
The "spring" is a rubber band looped thru the hole in the flip cup then round the bottom of the pivot bracket.  Use a rubber band with just enough tension to lift the cup up to the upper ramp.  You could use a weight instead of the rubber band if you wish.  
You could assemble this to have the flip cup on either the left or the right.  I had thought of making it wall mounted with more than 2 ramps but the capacity of this unit matches our household production and consumption nicely.

comments.text: By all means, feel free to design your own printable ramps as a remix of this design.  My general philosophy is to design things using the most appropriate material and method for function, aesthetic and ease of manufacture of the part being designed.  If you wanted a design that used printable ramps, you would either need to have a 3D printer with a large bed (say 300 x 300), or you would need to design using shorter ramps (therefore less egg capacity), or you would need to design so that each ramp can be made from multiple parts clipped, bolted or glued together.  Personally, I consider using a few cheap pieces of timber moulding for the straight parts is quicker and simpler to make and more aesthetically pleasing than trying to make it all printable. title: K40 Laser Engraver Red Dot Upgrade

description.text:
In review of the laser locator ideas/concepts...I've found that the cross hair principle was not good enough (for me). The ones that have two line lasers mounted to an air assist would require re calibration after removing to clean the focal lens (which should be done every time you use the laser). The dual line lasers mounted to the bracket that holds the head would eliminate this issue, but I have found that the thickness of the lines is not as narrow as I would prefer. I've reviewed a couple concepts that include a combiner lens ( the lenses cost between 40 and 60) and are somewhat complex to set up and maintain. This design allows for a standard red dot laser to be moved into the laser path for "Initial" location and slid out of the way when in operation.

The pros to this concept are: 1) Using the same focal lens as the CO2 laser will provide the EXACT location. 2) Passing the red dot laser through the focal lens will narrow the red dot to roughly the same size as the CO2 laser giving you pinpoint precision. 3) Aids in finding the focal point as you now can visually find the "sweet" spot.

The cons to this concept are: 1) you cannot use the red dot laser during operation.

title: FLSun Kossel MKS Gen L v1.0 Board Mount

description.text:
Replacement for the acrylic board mount that comes with the FLSun Kossel kit. Mine cracked when I first installed it because I bumped the board while setting the printer in place. The cracked corners finally fell off and I love the exposed look but figured I'd make a few improvements.

First, I moved the aluminum mounting holes closer to the center of the piece so that they would be less likely to snap off in the future and added an alignment bar so that it will hold the board a bit stiffer in place on the frame.

Second, I added standoffs to the mounting holes for the board. The original acrylic was all 5mm deep and the solder points dug into it and and forced it to flex if you tightened the screws too much. Making the board 3mm deep and the standoffs 2mm tall gave me the same height as the original board while still allowing room so that the solder points wouldn't been digging in.

Third, mostly cosmetic because I was going from a piece of see through acrylic to translucent plastic but also to cut down on the amount of plastic I needed to use to make it, I added a window to the back for the Makerbase logo to show through.

description.text:
The NEMA 14 motor on my Solidoodle 4 burned up after about 3 days of use.  As sad as this was, a little research showed that apparently the motor was being overpowered and thus overheated.  I happened to have a spare NEMA 17 lying around so I made an adapter!  I machined mine out of aluminum but I made holes for nuts so it can be 3d printed.  
My machine does jog now, and it's much much quieter, however it occasionally skips steps, which makes printing nearly impossible.  My NEMA 17 is the 48mm version, and I suspect that it is now under-powered, as it sometimes binds despite being at full current.  I'm hoping that Solidoodle with replace my fried NEMA 14 with a shorter NEMA 17.

comments.text: Have you tried adjusting the pots on the controller? Also, you will have to change the accel and jerk profiles on the firmware. This should fix your step skipping issues. The board on the solidoodle should have no problem driving a double or single stack nema 17 (even on the nema 14 port).

description.text:
I've had my eye on Hybryda's excellent Darth Vader bust and I decided once I got my CR-10 to print it full size. Then I thought, I wonder if I can hollow it out? So I did.
I've broken it up into pieces, you'll see the mask is in one piece, but I've also cut the chin off to make it easier to print the mask and chin separately. Here's the Flite Test Vlog:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-H76d7_7qSs

Watched the vlog and saw how they cut and hollowed it out post printing and taped the head back on and figured I could tidy that process up a bit.

I added holes in the bottom for wire routing (not pictured) and redesigned the motor mounting to hold different sized motors. The screw slots have a maximum spread of 23mm center to center and will fit M3 screws.

The inner cavity is 83mm wide at the thinnest point so there shouldn't be any FC placement issues either.

Overall it's a bit bigger than the original. When I imported the stl and did the mesh conversion the size got blown up to a few hundred percent so I scaled it down and it's not perfect but the motor measurements are sound.

This is a LARGE print (v12 files). At it's greatest extents it is 450mm wide, around 350mm rotated, which as of this writing is not good! I'll need to be shrinking this down since cutting it in half to print kinda defeats my purpose for doing this.

UPDATE:
The v18 files can fit in a 200mm x 200mm print area. The original v12 files probably can't fit an M3 screw as it turns out but an M4 should work and an M5 would be a little tight, M3 could work with a washer I guess. The v18 maximum screw spacing is now 20mm and the slots should fit an M3 or M4 no problem but not an M5. The inner cavity is now 43mm so still no FC problems hopefully.

Fusion360

I imported the stl and used mesh to body conversion. Before I did that though I had to lower the poly count which is why it's a little blockier.

I split the body and unfortunately the shell tool wouldn't work so I had to carve it out manually.

I then added the clips to hold the head on.

I remixed my own thing! The next obvious thing to do with the Offspring band logo is to add it to a guitar pick (plectrum). The print looks good, right? :-)
I added a second version of the pick; reduced the relief on the logo and thickened the pick; the .8mm version was floppy when printed at 0.2mm resolution; if your printer can handle it, use 0.1mm.

The successful build you see is using Makerware, 1 shell, 100% fill, .2mm layer height.  I used manual pausing to change the filament, and it came out looking quite nice!  You can use Z-pause to do the same thing, I suppose.  I printed up an earlier version at .1mm, but there were a lot of early fails; probably need to re-level my build plate.

description.text:
This is a Z-axis top left and right set with a vibration damping O-ring.

The O-ring is a #48 O-ring (5/8" OD, 3/8" ID, 1/8" thk, available at any hardware store plumbing section)

The Z-axis threaded rods will rest against the O-rings instead of plastic on the stock Prusa guides. This removes the noisy vibration when the Z-axis threaded rods occasionally light up from machine vibration.

The geometry of the O-ring still allows for the threaded rod to float inside of the guide, which I guess is intentional in the original design.

I used a file to clean up the 8mm hole for the smooth rods. Just a little. to tune the press fit onto the threaded rods. Don't use excessive force pushing onto the smooth rods.
Use a round file to clean up 8mm ID hole. Tune fit onto smooth rod to light press fit.

description.text:
Courtesy of GearBest°, I recently received this printer and I wanted to share my thoughts and experiences.
Through time I will update this post and upload each upgrades in this collection.

If you get interested by this printer here is a 12% off coupon code offer by GearBest : "GBTE"

° affiliate

First thoughts

While I was waiting for it I've seen a lot a reviews which weren't really laudatory, but actually, now that I'm using it, I find it pretty interesting for its price.
For sure at a such low cost it needs a few upgrades. But nothing impossible - far from it.

First thing I want to comment is the pictures that Tronxy uses (and other printer brand). Ok we can't wait too much from low cost printers, but there are some things to pay attention. As for exemple, on this picture, where are the cables? where are the endstops? why are the rails black where there are cuted?

Ok must of us won't pay attention to the perfect good looking of a printer -even if we love our machines- but to me it is important to take a look closer to the cable management of a printer before to buy it. In this case, cable management is not a big deal, can be done cleanly, and most important there won't be any trouble during prints. As for exemple, to what I have read, this is absolutly not the case of the X5.

Unboxing and Build

Packaging is approved!!! When I received it the cardboard had a hard life time during the shipment, but absolutly no parts were damaged ☺

The build went without any problem, I spent around 10hours to build it, but I admit that I wasted a lot of time by sorting out all the screws and managing the cables as clean as possible.

The frame is more robust than I thought. The acylic box for the PSU, LCD and Melzi board is great! but it take a bit of extra space, so like many other X3 owners I add feet to the printer (using some V-slot cut-off I had) and store the box under the printer.
At that point there was 2 things I planed to change :
• the bed crucially needed to be stabilized - done
• the belt idlers could be changed - done

For the bed I've found here on thingiverse a great stabilizer from Reeydz, but I added a way to tension the wheels.
For the belt idlers, I found one from idig3d which also tension the belt.It looks great andgots great feedbacks so give it a look. But it uses the same too wide bearings, and the way it is printed, i'm afraid that it brake after mounthes of use...so I chose to design my own using smaller bearings ; works a treat and i didn't need to add tensions to the belts.

Build is done! Time to first calibration.

First Calibrations

PIDs calibrations.
Extruder
Run the auto-tune command : M303 E0 S200 C8
Results :
Kp= 9.41;
Ki= 0.62;
Kd= 35.58;

Bed
Run the auto-tune command : M303 E-1 S60 C8
Results :
Kp= 196.0;
Ki= 33.0;
Kd= 290.0;

Enter those values in the EEprom and test. (results can be different for each printers)

From ambient temp (23°C) :
Extruder reach the 200°C in 1min45s.
Bed reach the 60°C in 2min20, and 90°C in 6min.

Hot end temp graph got too much oscillations, but it's less than +/- 1°C. Though I've tried to manualy change the PID values but I didn't success to killed those oscillations...
At first look bed temp graph looks great, but I measured the temp with a laser thermometer and temp wasn't good. 83°C instead of the 90°C read by the printer. This is an offset to note down when I'll print warping plastic.(not a big deal for PLA)

Also, like all PCB heat bed, center of the bed "is at the reached temp" (actually not) and temp slightly decrease to the edge of the bed. Which makes some spot of the bed at 78°C instead of 90°C => huge temp offset!

XYZ step calibrations.
Just to be sure, I've tested them.
For the X and Y axis I taped a needle to the carriage and the bed to take measurements.
For the Z axis I used a string for best measurments.
I tested on 200m motions, and everything was perfect from factory.
X and Y step/mm : 100.0 step/mm
Z step/mm : 400.0 step/mm

Extruder calibrations
There is more to say about the extruder. To me it needs to be changed, but lets try it and see what it can do.
Feeder setup
I don't like the way it is said to be set in the build video. It doesn't give enough pressure to offers a reliable and constant extrusion. Hopfully the fixed part of the feeder has a M3 thread. With a M3x40mm screw and somme M3 washers I set it this way.

This way it will be adjustable, and able to add more pressure. It is still not perfect, but works better.

E-step calibration:
•Heat the hot end to 190°C
•Mark the filament 12cm far from the feeder
•Extrude 10cm of filament
•Measure distance between the feeder and the mark. "x"

Get the filament through the feeder should be MUCH MORE easy. I spent a lot time trying and trying, until I unscrewed the tube connector and succeed! (<=it will need to be changed)

If "x"=20mm E-step is good.
If "x">20mm, underextrusion, increase E-step
If "x"<20mm, overextrusion, decrease E-step

My result : E-step=100.0 step/mm

Calibrations done. Time for first prints ☺

To-Do List

• Bed stabilizer - link
• Belt idlers - link
• Z min endstop accuracy
• Retraction tests
• X/Y square tests
• Bridge tests
• Extruder modifications
• Cooling fan?

title: Oculus Rift Rifle / Gun Stock Remix for 3/4" PVC & 6-32 screws

description.text:
This is a remix to make the PVC pipe edition fit with a standard 3/4" schedule 40 PVC pipe. The original was based on an assumed 1" outer diameter, which is a bit narrower than an actual 3/4" pipe. I changed the two piece design into clamshells, so you only need one screw/nut per clamp. I recreated the magnet slots to use 3mm x 18mm Neodymium magnets. Lastly, I changed the hex nut size to accommodate 1/2" 6-32 screws and nuts, instead of the harder to find (in the US) metric screws. (Edit: better go with 3/4" 6-32 as the 1/2" might be too short)

You should be able to buy all the hardware from Home Depot. Everbilt Machine Screws #6-32 1/2 inch, #6-32 hex nuts, 3/4" Schedule 40 PVC pipe, Magnet Source 18mm disc neodymium magnets. So this is basically the 'Murican version (no metric hardware).

No change to the shoulder stock section, but I'm including it anyway, so you don't have to hunt for it. Clearly it could use some cleanup, as I'm new at this and modified it in TinkerCAD. Works well enough for me, so I thought I'd upload it.

You'll need to print the Touch cradles, and slide a magnet into the slot from inside the cradle (friction fit, no glue needed). Print the shoulder stock and stock holder. Print at least 2 pipe clamps. I'd consider printing an extra clamp, so you can have a 3rd spot on your pipe. Handy for that P90 grip.

Glue the magnets into the bigger disc spaces in clamps, making sure to line up the polarity. These are fairly strong magnets, so use decent glue. I'm using E6000, and hoping it holds.

My post print photos are using overly long 1" screws that I had on hand. Also, two of the clamps are the older 2 piece design, closer to the original version (but for 6-32 screws).

Note: Someone had this printed and found the 1/2" screws too short. Might be best to go with 3/4" bolts. Sorry about that.

I didn't print the shoulder stock with supports, and it drooped, so I'd suggest doing so with supports. The pipe clamps can be printed without supports if printed on edge, as can the Touch cradles. Though the stock adapter may need some cleanup, due some bridging.

Don't forget to print 2 Touch cradles, with one copy mirrored. The neodynium magnets were so strong, they kept popping the magnets out of the Touch cradles (super glued in), so the final version has them pop in from above, with a 1mm gap on the bottom, so they sit on the inside of the cradle. Just make sure to line them up N to S when they mate. I originally stacked the disc magnets together, and marked a line down one side, so I could line them up afterward.

Prints fine with Cura, but someone had problems printing it with Prusa Control and/or Slic3r.
I got screws way longer than they needed to be. These were 1", I'd say go for 1/2". Touch cradle view from above with magnet inserted into it's slot. The crud on top is old super glue.

description.text:
This is a E3D V6 Clone fan duct which can simply be clipped over the cooling fins. The fit is so tight it supports its own weight plus the weight of the stock Anet A8 40 mm cooling fan. I use it in my setup in combination with the carriage here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2099577. This design allows more air flow and therefore more cooling than the crappy mini fan which came with my clone. I had to design it, because there was no satisfying solution available on thingiverse. The designs I found were either not fitting or restricting the air flow to much. The Duct was designed in Autodesk Inventor Professional 2016. I included the .ipt file, so you can modify it if you like.

Meassurements:

  • Radiator diameter = 22 mm
  • Space between hotend mounting cap and heater block = 31 mm (In reality I have additional 3-4 mm space to the hotend)

So if you have the same meassurements you can print this duct and use it. I hope I could help at least someone and contribute to the community somehow. Thank you!

description.text:
Warning! This is only a concept, 3D printed plastic is not fire proof and I accept no responsibility for injury caused by this cotton bud gun.

I printed this as proof of concept, it uses a mini hob lighter (available on EBay) to launch a cotton bud (ear swab) cut in half and put down the barrel cotton end first (slightly dampened). I printed the chamber separate to ensure no supporting structure was inside, before gluing it to the bottom of the gun using PVC Pipe Cement (type used by a plummer). The barrel may print with support, I used a thin screwdriver to push this out.

When the glue is was dried, I put the half ear swab cotton end first (after a little lick) in the barrel, put the lighter in the chamber hole, carefully squeezed the trigger for about 8 seconds to let some gas in (not all the way as to light the lighter), then aimed and squeezed the trigger all the way in to activate the piezoelectric ignition.
